article.headline: Michigan 55, Delaware State 50
article.story: ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Lester Abrams scored 12 points for a poor-shooting Michigan, which survived a second-half collapse to beat unheralded Delaware State 55-50 on Monday night. Michigan (7-1) led 30-14 at halftime on 38.2 percent (10-for-26) shooting. Delaware State shot 33.3 percent (7-for-21) before the intermission. The Hornets' 14 points were the fewest scored in a half against Michigan since it began playing at Crisler Arena in 1967. Delaware State (1-5) went on a 16-4 run in the second half to pull to 39-32 with 11 minutes to play. The Hornets closed to 50-49 in the final minute before Michigan ended the game on a 5-1 run, beginning with Daniel Gorton's driving layup with 50 seconds left to put the Wolverines ahead 52-50. Terrance Hunter scored 22 points and grabbed eight rebounds for Delaware State. He was 7-for-10 from the field and 2-for-2 from 3-point range. Aaron Williams added 10 points. The Hornets improved their shooting to 55 percent (11-for-20) after the intermission to Michigan's 38.9 percent (7-for-18). Dion Harris and Bernard Robinson, finished with 11 and 10 points, respectively, for Michigan. J.C. Mathis added four points end seven rebounds.
